1330	$fb_import_a62cf00283b51c8b269b111262b1e1b8	1	9	Yes, this is called pantheism! But for Spinoza, I believe it is more exact to say "substance monism", meaning there is only one substance which is God or Nature, and everything else is only a mode of that one substance. So when Spinoza says everything is necessary both de re and de dicto, he is not saying everything exists by itself or occurs independently. However, that everything follows from one reality in a necessary way, and the idea of could have been otherwise only appears, because we imagine an external standpoint that does not actually exist.\n \nMoreover, for freedom, he does not accept the Principle of Alternate Possibilities at all, because PAP already assumes contingency, and contingency is precisely what he opposes to at that metaphysical level. So for him, freedom is not about like having options but it's more about acting from the necessity of ones own nature rather than being pushed blindly by external causes. That is why God is perfectly free and humans are free only insofar as they could understand the causes that determine them, and the feeling that we could have done otherwise comes from ignorance of those causes, not from real alternatives in nature.\n \nAaaand, necessity does not erase causal relations but grounds them, because saying everything is necessary does not mean nothing depends on anything else, it means everything is determined through an ordered causal chain within Nature itself, so dependence and causation still exist but they are not contingent relations, they are necessary relations between modes.\n \nLastly, the example when I tap my phone, my finger really causes the screen to respond, and my finger really depends on my hand, my hand on my arm, and so on, but none of this implies contingency in the sense of metaphysical openness (?), and that's because given the total state of "Nature" at that moment, my finger necessarily moved and the phone necessarily responded, so interaction does not make things contingent, it only shows how necessity unfolds through the  causal determination or of some sort.\n \nThe deeper disagreement here is that you are using a framework where freedom requires alternatives and causation implies contingency, while Spinoza uses a framework where freedom means self-determination through understanding, causation is internal and necessary, and necessity is not static or isolating but dynamic and productive, so nothing disappears in his system except the idea that things could have been otherwise in an absolute sense.	\N	2025-12-18 14:15:59.486+00	2025-12-30 12:58:16.709198+00
