2808	$fb_import_53391615e2118c4ecd5c0ff38c12b5a2	1	5	I apologize for my long message too:\n\n1. I'm not using language to point at something beyond language & declaring it inaccessible. I'm saying that the very notion of 'beyond language' is a linguistic construction. When you say 'what lies beyond X', you've already employed language to create that category. There's no contradiction in language articulating itself own primordiality, since that's what self-founding discourse does. The Word doesn't need something prior to justify itself: Truth is True\n\n2. Yes, **something** was happening before humans existed: molecular processes, matter interacting. But "DNA replicating" as a coherent, intelligible phenomenon is linguistically constructed. The molecular interactions don't come pre-labeled like that, those are human concepts organizing undifferentiated physical processes into meaningful patterns.\n\nRE: your bridge example, that we parse this as 'structural failure due to miscalculated load-bearing capacity' is linguistic work, the bridge doesn't "know" it's following F=ma, we describe its behaviour using that framework.\n\nYou want to say the pattern "predates the word by billions of years", but "pattern" is already a concept. Patterns don't exist pre-made in nature waiting to be discovered, they're intelligible structures we create through linguistic-conceptual articulation.\n\n3. The gap between representation and instantiation that you're preserving is itself a linguistic distinction. 'Instantiation' and 'representation' are concepts in your theoretical framework. You're not accessing pre-linguistic instantiation and then describing ityou're creating a conceptual model where these categories do explanatory work.\n\nWhen you say 'DNA the molecule is instantiation, "DNA" the word is representation,' you've created two objects through language and asserted a relationship between them. But I can't verify this relationship by checking 'DNA itself' against your description, because any checking I do uses the same conceptual apparatus you've already deployed.\n\nA structure "being what it is" already presupposes identity, persistence, boundaries, all conceptual. There's no pure "being what it is" that exists outside of language. What something IS - its thingness, its having properties & relations - is already linguistically mediated.\n\nThese ideas that you're presenting is trying to preserve the idea that language represents pre-existing structure, but every model you build uses language to articulate structure, relations, distinctions. This is prosopoeia, creating conceptual categories & then reifying them, treating these linguistic constructions as if they are things themselves.\n\nYou would place the beginning of universe in the Big Bang as a temporal-material framework. I'm situating the beginning of the universe as here, now, where language creates the possibility of past, present & future as coherent categories.	\N	2025-12-23 06:08:22.485+00	2025-12-30 12:58:17.456158+00
