2820	$fb_import_65e0a50b106ff8d246c418b73003436c	1	5	> Language mediates intelligibilty, but mediation presupposes there was something to be mediated in the first place. \n\n"You're confusing 'language as such', the transcendental condition of intelligibility, with 'particular linguistic formulations'the specific words, concepts, and theories we use at any given time.\n\nWhen I say 'language is generative,' I don't mean 'whatever we happen to say becomes true.' I mean: the capacity for articulation, differentiation, and relation-making is the condition for anything to be intelligible at all. That capacityLanguage with a capital L, the Logosdoesn't 'need correcting.' What needs correcting are our particular attempts to articulate phenomena adequately\n\n> Language often needs correcting and fixing and always has to adapt. If language determines perception. Then it need not corrective action but it constantly does.\n\nWhat's doing the correcting? More language. We don't correct language by accessing some pure, pre-linguistic reality and comparing our words against it. We correct language through languageby creating better distinctions, more coherent frameworks, concepts that do more explanatory work.\n\nWhen Newtonian physics was 'corrected' by Einsteinian relativity, we didn't access 'reality itself' independent of conceptual frameworks. We moved from one linguistic-conceptual system to another. This correcting happened within language, through refinement of our own idea-structures.\n\nLanguage doesn't determine perception in the sense that 'if I call the sky green, it becomes green'. Language determines perception in the sense that having a perception as a structured, intelligible experience of anything-as-something requires linguistic-conceptual apparatus. Language orders the world not from "nothing", but from "no-thing-in-particular". Going back to the sky example, that 'no-thing-in-particular' becomes 'the sky' & 'blue through linguistic articulation.\n\nLanguage doesn't 'need corrective action' because it 'fails to match reality.' Language needs refinement because the process of linguistic articulation is how we explore and constitute intelligible reality. Every correction is language discovering more about itself, creating new distinctions, finding more coherent ways to organize experience. That's generative, not representative	\N	2025-12-23 08:04:40.545+00	2025-12-30 12:58:17.456158+00
