3056	$fb_import_664ca5b92b0cc3a947ca3a420d642754	1	5	>Animals that dont have language cant experience real things? Seems absurd. \n\nI am staying disciplined hereanimal "experience" might be radically different. We don't know, but the moment we try to dscribe their experience, we're using OUR linguistic categories. I'm not saying they experience nothing, but we have no access to that.\n\n>I think it again reduces to my proposal of us using the observer as the instantiator instead of language, because i think it is more defensible than saying that language is the instantiator of reality. \n\nBut what is an 'observer' apart from linguistic-conceptual articulation? 'Observer' is already a concept, it presupposes distinctions between self & world, subject & object etc.  When you say 'the phenomenon of there even being an observer to experience things is more interesting,' you're absolutely right. But that phenomenon is linguistic. The emergence of the observer, the splitting of experience into experiencer and experienced, the capacity for self-reflectionthese arise with and through language. Not temporally after language, but as the same generative process.\n\n> We only really live in the virtual since we only have access to the physical real through our senses. We reconstruct what it might be into the virtual based on these senses.\n\nIs there any need for a physical "real" that we can never access? Why can it not just be the ongoing, generative process of creation? Not as a virtual copy of something else, but the only reality we can meaningfully speak of - reality as linguistically constituted\n\n> And this is where im stumped. It could be God, the self justifying reference, Logic itself, reason, or whatever. But it doesnt need us.\n\nThis is the point I don't agree with the most, that "it doesn't need us"! This is where we diverge most sharplyyou're imagining some complete eternal structure & we're just optional add-ons. But no, the generative process requires participation. God becomes God through creating. The writer discovers their characters through writing. The Word thinks itself into being. God knowing himself through His creation.\n\nYour conception of your atemporal graph is dependent on YOU. It needed YOU, your words, your experience in order to exist. You are the vertices instantiating themselves. This isn't solipsism or idealism in the usual sense. I'm not saying 'only minds exist' or 'we make up reality arbitrarily.' I'm saying: intelligible realitystructure, relation, meaning, orderis the product of linguistic-experiential participation\n\nWe are necessary, not as optional observers, but as the medium through which the universe becomes ordered. We are how God knows Himself, through the process of divine self-articulation. Creation is not God making something separate from Himselfit's God differentiating Himself into intelligibility. And who is speaking for God? It is us, his world, reality is alive, our words live! A song needs its singers, a story needs its tellers.	\N	2025-12-23 10:04:09.851+00	2025-12-30 12:58:17.633033+00
